{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958022801/0180.xml":{"full_text":"THE\nUNION\nJOURNAL\u2019S\nEditorial Page\nFriday, February 28,1958\nOptimistic\nPreview\nHERE IS REASON to be optimistic\nabout the election prospects of liberal\nT\ncandidates for public office in the 1958\ncampaign\u2014but. as the Committee on Poli\ntical Education has pointed out, political\nvictories don\u2019t grow on trees.\nThere\u2019s a lot of work involved a\nchallenge to liberal political groups and to\nlabor to do an effective job between now\nand November.\nAs COPE Dir. James McDevitt has\nnoted, there are four reasons to believe\nthat the people will score a large number\nof victories at the polls. These include a\nfeeling among many voters that this will\nbe a crucial election directly affecting\ntheir future welfare; the reaction to un\nemployment, which has been growing\nsteadily; the success of organized labor in\nhelping many new voters to register; the\nincreased effectiveness of state and city\nlabor bodies where mergers have oc\ncurred\nBut the translation of these factors\nInto victories on election day will require\nhard work by labor\u2019s political arms.\nIt will be as in the past a matter of\nmaking certain that every possible labor\nvoter is registered, that he knows the is\nsues and the voting records of candidates,\nthat he gets to the polls on election day.\nIt is not too early now to be complet\ning plans for that kind of political work\nin the months ahead.\nSees Good In\nUnemployment\nTHIS is THE story of a man who can\nlook at a long line of unemployed\nworkers and enjoy it This is the story of\na man who likes to ride by unemployment\noffices and look at the jobless in line for\ntheir unemployment compensation. This is\na story of a man who thinks America may\nbe better off because of the recession.\nThe man is Irving B. Hexter of Cleve\nland, publisher of some industrial publica\ntions put out by the Industrial Publishing\nCorporation, 812 Huron Road, Cleveland.\nMr Hexter publishes a monthly booklet\ncalled, \u201cOne Publisher\u2019s Viewpoint.\" The.\nJanuary booklet issued by Mr. Hexter con\ncludes with these words:\n\"The most salutary thing in our\ncity\u2014and probably yours\u2014is to ride by\nthe main office of the Ohio State Un\nemployment Commission and see the\nhundreds of people waiting in a never\nreceding line for their unemployment\nchecks.\n\u201cThe employed can\u2019t help think,\n'there but for the grace of God go I.\u2019\nAnd maybe they\u2019ll go back to work a\nlittle harder, with their eyes on their\njobs rather than on their watches. If\nthat can be accomplished in America,\nwe will all be better off for the reces\nsion.\nIt is ironic that we learned of this\nstory during Brotherhood Week, a period\nset aside to urge people to practice un\nderstanding toward others and to show\ncompassion for their fellow-man. It is be\ncause of the expression of such calloused\nattitudes toward human suffering as those\nby Mr. Hexter that there is a need for\nreminding us of the great need to make\nBrotherhood a year 'round practice.\nIt has been such a long time since we\nread such comments about the misfortune\nof others that we forgot how revolting\nsuch comments can be.\nGovernor\nLate\nAs\nUsual\nFTER THE state\u2019s jobless rolls had in\ncreased for the 20th straight week\nA\nand set a record high for the fifth straight\nweek, Gov. C. William O\u2019Neill finally\nsays he regards the unemployment situa\ntion as Ohio\u2019s No. 1 problem.\nSo what does he intend to do about it\nafter such tardy recognition of the prob\nlem? Why, he's naming a couple commit\ntees \u201cto study\u201d the situation and report to\nhim the last week in March\nWe think the Governor has been too\nslow to recognize the seriousness of the\nsituation. And we think he is stalling for\nmore time when he calls for a \u201cstudy\u201d of\nthe problem.\nWe also think he has been reluctant\nto admit the seriousness of the situation\nbecause of his Administration\u2019s failure to\nincrease unemployment compensation\nduring the last Legislature and because\nof its stand against supplemental unem\nployment benefits (SUB).\nIt has been evident to many for some\ntime that unemployment was the state\u2019s\nNo. 1 problem and that Ohio\u2019s unemployed\nwere being made to suffer needlessly un\nder the state\u2019s pitifully inadequate unem\nployment compensation law.\nApparently the Governor had hoped\nthat the situation would correct itself be\nfore people started to demand positive ac\ntion and began wondering why his Admin\nistration has blocked SUB and failed to\nincrease compensation to more decent\nlevels.\nThe number of workers receiving un\nemployment compensation for one week\nor more stood at 190,344 as of Feb. '15,\n4\na new all-time high under the Ohio law.\nWhat is there to \u201cstudy\u201d about that?\nWe urged the Governor nearly a month\nago to call a special session of the Legisla-\nture for the sole purpose of increasing\nunemployment compensation. We also\nhave urged him to abandon his position\nagainst SUB.\nPeople are standing in line for day-old\nbread. This is no time for a \u201cstudy.\u201d This\nis a time for action. As Dr. Arthur F.\nBurns, President Eisenhower\u2019s former\nchief economic adviser said last week, the\ncurrent recession will be ended only by\n\"massive\u201d government intervention.\nMorgan Says:\nCan Ike Face Facts?\nA NEWS SERVICE moved a Washing\nton bulletin which read as follows:\n\u201cPresident Eisenhower today expressed\ndeep concern over unemployment hard\nship, and said he is confident the picture\nwill start to brighten in March.\u201d\nLess than an hour later the same agen\ncy cleared a new lead on the story which\nbegan as follows: \u201cPresident Eisenhower\nexpressed confidence today the economic\ndowntrend is about over. He said March\nshould see the start of a rise in employ\nment and the \u2018beginning of the end\u2019 of the\ndownturn.\u2019\nEach lead was factually correct. The\ndifference was in emphasis. But the dif\nference was important. The first bulletin\nalmost automatically suggested a head\nache which might read \u201cIke Worried\nOver Nation\u2019s Jobless.\u201d From the second\nit was easier to draw a happier line, such\nas\n\u201cPresident Sees Employment Rise\nSoon.\u201d\nU. S. publishers are predominantly Re\npublican, but this is not to.suggest that the\nwire service deliberately figured its cli\nents would be more satisfied with a \u201cposi\ntive approach\u201d to the recession story\u2014\nthough the publishers would, of course, or\nthey wouldn\u2019t be human. The change of\nemphasis struck me as reflecting\u2014inad\nvertently\u2014the Administration\u2019s own diffi\nculty in facing up to bad news.\nBad economic news is political dyna\nmite of the most explosive kind and this is\nan election year. Even the most equilibrat\ned, modernized Republican feels a twinge\nof fear when he hears a Democrat holler\n\u201cHoover depression!\u201d at him.\nThe important question at this junc\nture, however, is how squarely the Eisen\nhower regime can bear to look the facts in\nthe face after the inevitable political criti\ncism is put in its proper perspective.\nAs one New York bank economist said,\nin effect, today you can\u2019t just talk your\nway out of an economic downturn. But\nthat, unhappily, appears to be precisely\nwhat the Administration is trying to do.\nThere is a certain emphasis on prog\nress in housing, urban renewal, highway\nconstruction and the like, but many ex\nperts have long since pointed out the real\nestate lobby\u2019s successful resistance to pub\nlic housing for low and moderate-income\ngroups in any degree approaching real\nneed, and the lack of leadership to get the\nproper coordination in slum clearance,\nurban renewal and the road program.\nAs for the vaunted public works pump\npriming that the Post Office moderniza\ntion plan is supposed to represent, the $2\nbillion fund which the White House spoke\nof so glowingly looks better in a headline\nthan under a microscope.\nPlaying post office with the recession\nmay be fun. It may even be helpful. But\nthe Administration is going to have to\nthink up a more serious game than this.\nI\u2019m afraid, before we\u2019ve heard the last of\nrecession.\nThrough The Years\nWith The Toledo Union Journal\nFIFTEEN YEARS AGO\nFEBRUARY 26, 1943: The cost of living\nfor workers rose 7.3% higher over a year ago\naccording to statistical survey of the National\nIndustrial Conference Board, an employers\u2019\norganization Another Toledo industry\njoined the growing number of plants repudiat\ning AFL leadership and organization when the\nSurface Combustion Co. employes voted in fa\nvor of the UAW-CIO by a substantial major\nity in a NLRB conducted election at the Dorr\nSt. plant.\nTEN YEARS AGO\nFEBRUARY 24, 1948: Twenty-seven can\ndidates will compete today for the 16 posts com\nprising the top offices of the Local 12 execu\ntive board in the annual union election\nFour National Labor Union AFL pickets were\nattacked and beaten by a mob of 40 and one of\nthe pickets had to be hospitalized The\nNLRB has handled 105,000 cases in the twelve\nyears under the Wagner Act.\nFIVE YEARS AGO\nFEBRUARY 27, 1953: One hundred and\nsixty members of American Floor Surface Unit\nof Local 12 exhausted their patience in at\ntempting to reach an agreement on a new con\ntract and are backing their demands with\nstrike action The Local 12 Summer Camp\nWomen\u2019s Guild will hold its first rummage\nsale which will be held April24 and 25 with\nall proceeds going to send underprivileged\nchildren to camp According to a report by\nthe AFL Executive Council productivity in our\nprivate economy increased by 13 2 per cent\nfrom 1949 to 1952 while wages only increased\n7 per cent during the same period.\nA\nDrifting and Dreaming\noo\u2019ce\n\u00b0$0ras\n\n\nv..\nTTllJ-D\"TTTMTIIIM\nThink It Over\nCC1\nhe\nCone\nDRAWN pros THE\nAFLCIO news\nh\n7\nTarget: March 26, 1958\nBy PETE ZVARA\n1 IIMSIIINTIIITINNTNINH\nTO ILLUSTRATE the point I should like to\nmake, I want to tell you a story\u2014a story of\ntwo couples, friends and neighbors, no different\nthan you or I, or people we happen to know.\nNow, it so happened that ne of these cou\nPete Zvara\npies were perpetually argu\ning with each other, leading\na rather turbulent and even\n\u2014at times\u2014unhappy life.\nThe other couple, on the\nother hand, were getting\nalong like a pair of pro\nverbial doves, always happy,\nnever arguing and\u2014at least\nseemingly\u2014enjoying life to\nits fullest\nSo one day, following a\nhectic argument, the man\nwho never seemed to have\npeace in his family and very much upset over\nthe latest outburst in his household, said to his\nhappy neighbor:\n\"Tell me, why is it that you always get\nalong with your wife you people never\nseem to have any disagreements and both of\nyou are always so happy?\"\n\u201cWell,\" his neighbor replied sagely and\nwith a smile, \u201cit is really simple. When we\nfirst got married we made a joint decision\nthat in our family my wife shall always make\nthe small, the unimportant decisions, and that\nI\u2014as the head of the family\u2014would make all\nthe great and important decisions.\"\nAnd here he paused for a moment and\nthen continued:\n\u201cFor example my wife decides such unim\nportant decisions as to when we should buy\na new car, a new fur coat for herself or wheth\ner we should remodel our old home, or buy a\nnew one. As for me,\" he continued with the\nwise look of a sage, \u201cI decide questions like\nwhether or not we should admit Communist\nChina to the United Nations, what we should\ndo to counteract the Soviet Union in the cold\nwar, and so on.\u201d\nThat was it. That was the formula for hap\npiness in his household. And as he finished,\nhe patted his neighbor on the back and advised\nthat he should now go home, make up with\nhis wife and live happily ever after.\nI\nAT THIS POINT I am sure that we can all\nagree with this conclusion our \u201chappy\u201d neigh\nbor is living in a fool's paradise and he is kid\nding only himself.\nBut the point I want to make is that there\nare so many, many of our people who live and\nact just like the \u201chappy\" neighbor of our story.\nSo many of our people talk about great and\nmomentous problems, but forget the \u201clittle\"\nproblems that actually govern their very ex\nistence.\nHow many people do we know personally\nin our unions who spend most of their time\ncriticizing their unions and their leaders, but\nrefuse to attend meetings or to do anything\nto participate in the daily activities of their or\nganization in a sincere attempt to help them\nselves and their fellow members.\nIt is so simple, so easy to blame, to criti\ncize It is so much more difficult to pitch in\nand help.\nTHIS CONDITION Is even more wide\nspread in our political life Almost everyone\nI know\u2014and this certainly holds true with\neveryone\u2014has strong and positive opinions on\nall acts of government and most certainly of\nevery politician or government .official.\nBut when it comes to participating in our\npolitical life on the most elementary levels\u2014\nsuch as registering to vote and then actually\nvoting in elections\u2014tens of thousands of them\nare nowhere to be found.\nThe actions of governments\u2014from the\nprimitive days of the tribal chiefs to the enor\nmously complex governmental machinery of\ntoday\u2014have always been of tremendous Im\nportance to the governed.\nThis is terrible true today.\nEveryone knows, or should know, that to\nday governments make decisions that affects\nour everyday living, our bread and butter, our\nvery lives. Surely, under these circumstances,\nit would seem that all citizens would be on\nthe' alert at all times and participate to the\nmaximum degree possible to influence these\nacts.\nUnfortunately such is not the case.\nTODAY WE HAVE millions of our citizens\njobless\u2014and through no fault of their own. We\nhave other millions of our citizens who depend,\nin one form or another, on direct government\naid to sustain themselves. Social security and\nold age pensions are certainly excellent ex\namples.\nWe also have the millions who are jobless\ndepending on whatever unemployment com\npensation they receive. And as we all know,\nthese jobless pay benefits are so meager that\nfamilies dependent on it are barely able to\nsustain body and souls together.\nIsn't it a shame that here in our country.\nthe wealthiest, the most blessed in all history\nwith all the good things of life that our people\ncould possibly need, millions are suffering\nprivation, some even destitution!\nIF WE LIVED in a poor country, backward\nand without the enormous riches we were\nblessed with, one could understand suffering\nand hunger in the ranks of our people.\nIndia, Africa and other lands suffer and\nwant because they don't have even enough to\ngo around.\nBut not us, not our country.\nSo, what is needed? What must we do to\ncorrect this situation? What kind of actions\nmust we take to prevent this now officially\nrecognized recession from snowballing into a\nterrible depression?\nI know this might sound trite, yet it is\ntrue of that I am positive. Our people, the\ngripers, the bellyachers, the perpetual fault\nfinders should look at themselves and make up\ntheir minds that it is not enough just to talk,\nto complain. They must do something.\nAnd that something is to make sure that\nthey, and the members of their families who\nare old enough, must register if they are not\nnow registered. And, when election time comes\naround, they must vote.\nToday the government has the power to\ninitiate and follow through on programs that\ncan bring back prosperity jobs to our\npeople.\nToday the government is the only institu\ntion that can provide adequately for our needy,\nfor our jobless, for our aged.\nToday the government can regulate the\nvery existence of our labor unions and\nregulate it in such a way as to make them\nhelpless and impotent in our dealings with our\nemployers.\nThe proposed and so-called \"right-to-work\"\nlaw\u2014a law that has absolutely nothing to do\nwith the right of people to work\u2014is such a\nproposal in Ohio right now.\nIt takes so pitifully little to change the\ncourse of events to leave fear, recessions\nand suffering behind to seek and find hap\npiness and contentment and prosperity.\nThe very first step is to register and then\nto vote\u2014for people and for programs serving\nALL THE PEOPLE and not just the relative\nfew who already have more than they need.\nThe deadline for registering in Ohio is\nMarch 26. 1958.\nEPITAPH ON THE tombstone of a\nhypochondriac: \u201cI told you I was sick.\u201d\nORG4MZE TOLEDO10Q%^\nOfficial Publication of Organised Labor\nin Northwestern Ohio\nLABOR PRESS\nSsocanti\nI\nGrand\nAward\nWinner\nEntered at Toledo, Ohio, Post Office as second\nclass matter under the act of Aug. 24, 1912\nPublished Every Friday\nPublishing Office, 425 Winthrop Street\nToledo, Ohio\nFor Information Phone CH. 1-9126\nWalter Murphy\nBernard Stern\nPete Zvara\nWilliam Borden\nDerele Collins\nMelvin Zimkowski,\nEdmond A Pawlicki\nEditor\n.Associate Editor\n.Associate Editor\nSports Editor\nCirculation Manager\nJournal Cameramen\nOrville Beemer, Walter Murphy,\nCharles Ballard, Otto Beebe (Local 348),\nErnest Love (Local 1058) Board of Trustees\nDavid Huber\nDirector of Advertising\nTelephone Advertising Department\nCH. 4-4400 and CH. 6-1141\nMember Trade Union Advertising, N. T.\nIts Your Washington\nBy WILLARD SHELTON\nANYONE WHO doesn\u2019t understand what is meant by\nthe phrase \u201ctax loopholes\u201d could get a reasonably ac\ncurate idea from a little message from Prentice-Hall Inc.,\na business publisher, addressed to the \u201csuccessful busi\nnessman who wants to acquire a fortune.\u201d\nPrentice-Hall is advertising its new \"Tax Ideas Manual,M\npriced at $24.50, by candidly remarking to the \u201c25,000-a-year\u201d\nexecutive that if he wants to accumulate a pile of money in a\nhurry \u201cyou will have to use special tax methods to do it.\u201d\nAmong the \"special tax methods\u201d suggested is the usual\none of arranging ordinary income so that it becomes a capital\ngain, taxable at a lower rate than income pays. There is the\nfamily partnership dodge, pushed through the Senate several\nyears ago.\nThere appear to be, also. a gimmick on handling investment\nfrom dividends that gratifies high-income operators; a legal\nscheme for setting up a \u201cshort-term trust\u201d in which no taxes\nare paid for the life of the trust and the property eventually\nreverts to the person who created same; and a way in which a\nstockholder-executive-employe can gain \u201calmost fantastic dol\nlar accumulations.\u201d\nLegally there is nothing wrong in tax avoidance as distin\nguished from tax evasion. The law presumes that citizens will\ntake advantage of loopholes to avoid paying more than they are\ncompelled to pay.\nStill it is always instructive to find evidence that techniques\nof avoidance are available that the vast majority of citizens\ndon\u2019t dream of and couldn't use. People got indignant a genera\ntion ago when they learned that Morgan partners had success\nfully arranged their affairs so as to pay no income taxes or mere\nly nominal taxes. The loopholes today are more numerous and\nbigger\nSEN. HARRY FLOOD BYRD (D-Va.) says he will retire\nafter this session. He has been in the Senate since 1933 and his\ncontribution in 25 years has reared no monuments.\nThere is no \u201cByrd Act\u201d that contributes to the general\nwelfare and symbolizes his preeminence in some field or broad\nimportance. His leadership has built no schools or hospitals;\nhas contributed nothing outstanding in social insurance, in\ndustrial relations or other orderly approaches to inescapable\nmodern human needs.\nThe cloying negations of his influence in the Senate have\nbeen parallelled in his domination of his home state of Virginia.\nHe has shown neither compassion for nor understanding of the\nunquenchable aspiration of colored citizens for the first-class\nstatus in their own communities. He has led Virginia into a\nmorass of \u201cmassive resistance\u201d to which the end seems likely\nto be a closing of the public schools. Congress can easily escape\nhis legacy but the people of the state are not so fortunate.\nLetters To The Editor\nHere\u2019s Job For All\nTO THE EDITOR:\nThe lack of concern shown\nby this administration for the\nunemployed has my Yankee\nblood boiling. While pouring\nmillions of dollars into other\nnations to bolster their econ\nomy, our fellow men are los\ning their homes, cars and fur\nniture. Monies going down the\ndrain of Republican indiffer\nence to their plight. Charity\nis one of God\u2019s command\nments to us. It begins at home.\n1st Timothy\u20145-8 says\u2014\n\"But if any provide not for\nhis own, and specially for\nthose of his own house, he\nhath denied the faith, and is\nworse than an infidel.\u201d\nTherefore we are denied\nour God-given right to earn\nour bread by the sweat of our\nface. We desire jobs, not the\nNo! not BUC\npity\nof\nmen.\nbenefits the pittance of an\nunsound law.\nWe the American labor\nforce should back the policies\nof our worthy leaders. With\nout our shoulders at the wheel\nof, the labor movement, they\nare helpless. Our support is\nvital\nMake\nallowance\nfor\nmistakes, be willing to praise,\nnot to condemn every action.\nThe all-out war on the Unions\nis now on by big business. Do\nnot help them by destructive\ncriticism. If a Union man, be\na good one.\nWrite letters of protest to\nyour congressman demanding\naction. George can not do it\nall.\nYour future lies in the\nbalance, your letter may tip\nthe scales in your favor. Write\ntoday, tomorrow may be too\nlate.\nEDWIN F. RIFFLE,\nWillys Unit,\n6839 Lewis Avenue\nBulletin Board\nSaturday, March 1\nKIDS PARTY 10:00 A.M. Parlor A\nE. W. BLISS 1:30 P.M. Parlor A\nSTEEL TUBE 10:00-A.M. Parlor B\nTOLEDO STEEL SHOT 1:00 P.M. Parlor C\nSunday, March 2\nSPICER STEWARDS 8:30 P.M. Parlor A\nSPICER MEMBERSHIP 10:00 A.M. Parlor A\nMATHER SPRING 10:00 A.M. Parlor H\nMonday, March 3\nTOLEDO WIRE PROD. 8:00 P.M. Parlor C\nTuesday, March 4\nTILLOTSON 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nENSIGN 8:00 P.M. Parlor B\nSTANDARD EQUIPMENT 7:30 P.M. Parlor C\nCHAMP- GOLF LEAGUE 7:30 P.M. Parlor H\nWednesday, March 5\nDEVILBISS 7:30 P.M. Parlor A\nINT. HARVESTER 5:30 P.M. Parlor B.\nTILLOTSON 1:00 P.M. Parlor B\nALLIED WHEEL 4:15 P.M. Parlor H\nThursday, March 6\nDEVILBISS 10:00 A.M. Parlor A\nCHAMPION 11:30 A.M. Parlor A\nCHAMPION 7:30 P.M. Parlor A\nFORT PITT 8:00 P.M. Room 309\nCAMERA CLUB 8:00 P.M. Parlor C\nFriday, March 7\nW. O. NIGHTS 10:00 A.M. Parlor A\nW. O. DAYS 8:00 P.M. Scott High\nA. L. STEWARDS 2:30 P.M. Parlor A\nRATH. JONES 8:00 P.M. Parlor B\nAMERICAN FLOOR 8:00 P.M. Parlor C\nBUCKEYE PAINT 8:00 P.M. Conference Room\nLocal 12 Dues Office open all week Monday thru Fri\nday from 9:30 A.M. to 6:00 P. M.,Closed all day Satur\nday, Sunday and all holidays.\nOTHER LOCAL INION MEETINGS\nNEWSPAPER PRESSMEN\n2nd Tuesdav 7:30 P.M. Kapp's Hall\nPHOTO ENGRAVERS\n2nd Monday 5:30 P M. 61212 Huron St.\nBOOKBINDERS\n2nd Thursday 7 P.M. 912 Adams St.\nRETAIL CLERKS\n1st Wednesday 8 P.M. 21532 Summit St.\nMAILERS 5\n3rd Monday 6 P.M. 61212 Huron St.\nALLIED PRINTING TRADES COUNCIL\n1st Friday 612%2 Huron St.\nPRINTING PRESSMEN ASSISTANTS NO. 55\n4th Friday 6121 Huron St.\nCOMMUNICATION WORKERS, LOCAL 4319\n2nd Thursday 8:30 P.M. 70612 Monroe St.","height":"26784","width":"19584"}}
